Strings in C (Complete Beginner to Interview Level)

Strings are one of the most asked topics in C interviews. Interviewers ask both theory and coding questions.

1. What is a String?
A string is a sequence of characters ending with a special character called the null character ('\0').

Example:
H e l l o \0
The computer knows the string ends when it finds '\0'.

2. What is a Character Array?
In C, there is no built-in string data type.
Strings are stored as character arrays.
Example:
char name[6] = "Hello";

Memory:
Index   0   1   2   3   4    5
       +---+---+---+---+---+----+
Value  | H | e | l | l | o | \0 |
       +---+---+---+---+---+----+

Notice:
"Hello"

actually occupies 6 bytes, not 5.

Why?
Because of '\0'.

Why is '\0' Needed?
Suppose

char name[] = "Hello";
How does printf("%s", name); know where to stop?
It prints characters until it reaches

'\0'
Without '\0', it would continue reading garbage memory.

Character vs String
Character
char ch = 'A';
