Ways to Initialize Strings

Method 1
char name[] = "Hello";
Compiler automatically adds '\0'.

Method 2
char name[6] = "Hello";

Method 3
char name[] = {'H','e','l','l','o','\0'};

String Input
Method 1: scanf()
char name[20];

scanf("%s", name);

Problem:
If input is
Yash Sharma
Output

Yash

scanf("%s") stops at the first space.

Method 2: fgets() ⭐ (Recommended)
char name[50];

fgets(name, 50, stdin);

Input
Yash Sharma

Output
Yash Sharma

It reads spaces too.
Why not gets()?
Older C had
gets(name);

Problem:

No size limit.
Can cause buffer overflow.

So it is removed from the C standard.

Always use

fgets()
String Output
Using
printf("%s", name);
or
puts(name);



Important String Functions
All string functions are in

#include <string.h>
1. strlen()
Meaning
Returns the length of a string.
Syntax
strlen(string);

Example
char str[] = "Hello";
printf("%lu", strlen(str));
Output
5

Notice

It does not count '\0'.

Memory
H e l l o \0

Length = 5
Interview Question
Does strlen() count '\0'?
No.

